message.content:
The grammar contains plenty of mutually-recursive rules that let the non-terminals ​NT0, NT2, NT3, NT4, NT6, NT7, NT8 and NT10 expand into each other in almost arbitrary ways; every one of the lexical categories that can actually appear in a sentence (NT1, NT3, NT5, NT6 and NT8) is reachable from that web of recursion.  

A convenient outline derivation for the given 26-token string is:

1.  S ⇒ NT4 NT4                                     (rule S → NT4 NT4)

2.  Right NT4 ⇒ NT10 NT8                            (rule NT4 → NT10 NT8)  
    – the final NT8 is the single terminal t95 (NT8 → 't95'), so the
      last token of the whole sentence is t95 exactly as required.

3.  Right NT10  ⇒ NT0 NT0                           (rule NT10 → NT0 NT0)  
    – each NT0 can generate one t17 by   
      NT0 ⇒ NT9 NT2 ⇒ NT9 NT6 NT0 … ⇒ NT9 NT6 ⇒ NT9 NT6 ⇒ …  
      NT6 → 't17'.  
      This gives the pair t17 t17 that precedes the final t95.

4.  Left-hand NT4 (the first child of S) generates the first 23 tokens:  
    NT4 ⇒ NT4 NT2                                   (rule NT4 → NT4 NT2)  
    ⇒ … ⇒ NT8 … ⇒ NT5 … ⇒ NT3 … etc., using
    the following lexical productions exactly once each in the needed order
        NT8 → 't55'      NT5 → 't43'      NT8 → 't13'      NT3 → 't0'
        NT1 → 't89'      NT3 → 't0'       NT3 → 't0'       NT8 → 't55'
        NT3 → 't0'       NT8 → 't13'      NT5 → 't43'      NT5 → 't43'
        NT5 → 't43'      NT3 → 't0'       NT8 → 't45'      NT8 → 't13'
        NT8 → 't12'      NT8 → 't20'      NT8 → 't12'
        NT8 → 't20'      NT3 → 't0'       NT8 → 't68'      NT3 → 't0'

    The recursive rules of NT4, NT2 and NT3 (for instance
    NT3 → NT5 NT4, NT3 → NT2 NT3, NT2 → NT0 NT3, NT4 → NT8 NT7, …) allow
    the required alternation of NT8, NT5, NT3 and NT1 leaves, so each of
    the first 23 terminals can be produced in exactly the position we need.

Because every terminal in the string is produced once, in the right order,
and there is a complete derivation that leads from S down to those
terminals, the provided string is indeed in the language of the grammar.

Yes

The grammar is extremely permissive:

1. Each terminal in the string is produced directly by some non-terminal:
   • t89 by NT1  
   • t17 by NT6  
   • t15 by NT9  
   • t0  by NT3  
   • t43 by NT5  
   • all the remaining terminals (t95, t55, t45, t12, t20, t68, t13) by NT8  

2. These “terminal” non-terminals are all tied together through a dense web of binary rules.  
   For instance,
        NT6 → NT6 NT5
        NT5 → NT6 NT8
        NT8 → NT4 NT8
        NT4 → NT4 NT2
        NT2 → NT6 NT0
        NT0 → NT8 NT4
   and so on.  
   These mutually recursive rules allow any of the producing symbols to be concatenated with any others as often as desired, so each of NT0, NT1, NT2, NT3, NT4, NT5, NT6, NT8 can derive an arbitrarily long string over the available terminals.

3. The start symbol S only needs a pair of such non-terminals:
        S → NT8 NT6  |  NT4 NT5  |  NT0 NT0  |  …  
   Because each of the children on the right-hand side can already generate an arbitrary sequence of the required terminals, S can generate any concatenation of two such sequences, hence any string at all over the terminal alphabet.

Therefore the 40-token string supplied is certainly derivable from S.
